<br>
Okay, on to the critiques you provided.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://victoria.tc.ca/int-grps/books/techrev/bkatshrg.rvw">Mr. Slade</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> was certainly very critical, and obviously has an ideological opposition to the book. He attempts to link Objectivism to <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.auburn.edu/~johnspm/gloss/index.html?http://www.auburn.edu/~johnspm/gloss/fascism.html">Fascism</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->, a patently ridiculous claim. Fascism is not a right wing or conservative philosophy. Most often, statements attempting to link something to fascism (or <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.auburn.edu/~johnspm/gloss/index.html?http://www.auburn.edu/~johnspm/gloss/communism.html">Communism</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->) to something or someone are shallow attempts at demonization. On that same line, he constantly uses the term ‘Geek’ for some reason.<br>
<br>
He makes statements that I can find no supporting evidence of. He states “…nature. She hates it”, based on her appreciation of the work on humans. Also, he contends that if a passenger train was on the main line it would be hit by a freighter carrying needed medicine – where the hell did that come from? <br>
<br>
Raliroads - why didn’t Rand discuss other obvious transportations? Could it have been because the main character ran a railroad, and from her perspective it was the most important thing? No, it must be she was ignorant and lazy! <br>
<br>
As for Galt’s motor, well the book was Fiction (borderline SF), and his engine was supposed to get it power from (as I understood it) ambient electricity in the air. Hell, the way it was described it might have pulled power from the earth’s magnetic fields – how dare fiction not be perfect in its depiction of new technologies! The sonic weapon (I believe it was called ‘Harmony’ used the newly developed Rearden Metal) didn’t damage the transmitter because it was made of the new metal (previous attempts had all destroyed the transmitter), and it was finally destroyed when it was aimed at itself and destroyed the facility.<br>
<br>
But enough of this review, how about <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.skeptic.com/02.2.shermer-unlikely-cult.html">Mr. Shermer’s</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> – I found nothing to disagree with here. He is correct; Rand did become something of a cult leader (‘Guru’), and was probably a nasty witch.<br>
<br>
Here are a few quotes I consider key here:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  Criticism of the founder of a philosophy does not, by itself, constitute a negation of any part of the philosophy.<br>
<br>
Ayn Rand has probably influenced my thinking more than any other author. I have read all of her works, … even read the Brobdingnagian Atlas Shrugged no less than three times, plus once on audio tape for good measure. Thus I am not a blind critic. (Some of Rand's critics have attacked Atlas without ever reading it, and Objectivism, without ever knowing anything about it. I have encountered many of these myself. Even the pompously intellectual William Buckley spoke of the &quot;desiccated philosophy&quot; of Atlas, &quot;the essential aridity of Miss Rand's philosophy,&quot; and the tone of Atlas as &quot;over-riding arrogance,&quot; yet later confessed: &quot;I never read the book. When I read the review of it and saw the length of the book, I never picked it up.&quot; <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Nothing could be more irrational</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.) I accept most of Rand's philosophy, but not all of it.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And, with that, I close my argument on Atlas Shrugged, unless someone else wishes to continue it. You will either read it or not, love it or hate it. <br>
<br>
As for GM foods, you are preaching to the choir here. Ditto on raising their standard of living.  <p>Dr. Carstairs</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubestonnet.showPublicProfile?language=EN>bestonnet</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Fusion Starship Captain</span><br>  Posts: 383<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/21/02 11:31:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=91.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/16.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Objectivism</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> First, I made an error in an earlier post. In an attempt to be flip and clever (and I must admit it has been several years since I read the book), I misstated the actions of Ragnar Danneskjold. He did not sink ships indiscriminately, in fact he was very careful concerning the civilians. He would commandeer the cargo ships, and he only sank military vessels that attacked him. If I recall correctly, the crew’s of the cargo ships would be forced into small craft (but only under safe conditions) along with provisions and radios. Ragnar would take the ships and their cargos and sell them, depositing the moneys into bank accounts and earmarking it to go back to the taxpayers it had been seized from.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
